(STIF X) returns the `Short Time Interval Following' X. (STIF FOO) does not include the time point (EndFn FOO), but does include every time point in between (EndFn FOO) and (EndFn (STIF FOO)). The function STIF is used to state axioms which assert propositions about the world just after some TemporalThing (i.e., after an event ends, after a tangible object ceases to exist, etc.). Each of those propositions may or may not hold beyond the bounds of that short interval. Consider the axiom `after swimming, the swimmer is wet'. The swimmer is only known to be wet for a short time interval immediately following the swimming event, and so we use STIF to specify that short time interval in which the assertion of wetness will hold. Beyond that time, additional axioms would be required to decide whether the wetness would persist or not. Also see: STIB.

Whenever SLOT is an instance of ActorSlot, (SemelfactiveTypeFn SLOT) denotes the collection of all event types that are semelfactive with respect to SLOT, i.e., can be instantiated only once with a given individual playing the role SLOT in the event. Positive example: Dying is an element of (SemelfactiveTypeFn bodilyDoer), since the formula (and (isa ?X Dying) (bodilyDoer ?X ?P)) cannot be satisfied more than once over time, once ?P is fixed. Negative example: BirthEvent is not an element of (SemelfactiveTypeFn birthParent) -- though of course it *is* an element of (SemelfactiveTypeFn birthChild). Observe that we have to define `semelfactive' in this somewhat counterintuive way because in the Davidsonian conception of events adopted in Cyc events are particular occurrences -- and all event *particulars* can happen at most once! My particular pressing of the SpaceBar key now cannot happen again: any later such pressing would be another event, not *this* one. Consequently, we can't simply define semelfactive event types as those the instances of which can happen only once, since *all* event types in Cyc would have that property. In Cyc, the following 2 claims are equivalent: (i) the formula (isa ?X Dying) is satisfied only once (over time), (ii) the formula (isa ?X Dying) is satisfied by only 1 object.

A MathematicalFunctionOnScalars that is effectively the arithmetical operation of taking a number to a specified power (see ExponentFn), extended to all (measurable) ScalarIntervals. (ScalarExponentFn SCALAR EXP) is SCALAR^EXP, i.e. SCALAR to the power EXP. If SCALAR is a RealNumber, SCALAR^EXP is equal to (ExponentFn SCALAR EXP). If SCALAR is a MeasurableQuantity (q.v.), then SCALAR^EXP is also a measurable-quantity, and of a different "dimensionality" than SCALAR (see e.g. MultiDimensionalQuantity). More specifically, if SCALAR = (UNIT NUM), for some UnitOfMeasure UNIT and NumericInterval NUM, and EXP is a PositiveInteger, then SCALAR^EXP = ((UNIT^EXP) (ExponentFn NUM EXP)), where (UNIT^EXP) is the result of "multiplying" (via UnitProductFn) UNIT by itself EXP-1 times.

For example, (ScalarExponentFn (Meter 5) 2) is equal to 

  ((UnitProductFn Meter Meter) (ExponentFn 5 2)) ,

which is equal to (SquareMeter 25). And (ScalarExponentFn (Inch 5) 3) is equal to (CubicInch 125).

STIB
items.comment: An instance of IndividualDenotingFunction. When applied to an instance THING of TemporalThing, STIB returns the `Short Time Interval Before' THING. (STIB THING) does not include the time point (StartFn THING), but does include every time point in between (StartFn THING) and (StartFn (STIB THING)). The function STIB is used to state axioms which assert propositions about the world just before some TemporalThing. E.g., just before some event begins, or just before some tangible object comes into being. Whether the propositions hold beyond the bounds of the short interval specified depends the nature of the proposition. Consider the axiom `before launching, the Space Shuttle's fuel tanks are full'. The fuel tanks are only known to be full immediately before the launching event, and for some (measurable but potentially short) time interval before that launch, and so we use STIB to specify the time interval in which the assertion of fullness will hold. Before or after that time, additional axioms are required to conclude whether the tanks are full or not. Also see: STIF.

label: Cyc's knowledge about situation predicate representation
SituationPredicateRepresentationMt
items.comment: This microtheory stores basic definitional information about constants used for "non-Davidsonian" representation of situations, events and actions -- notably, it stores the definitions of SituationPredicate and it's specializations, EventPredicate and ActionPredicate (qq.v.). If you use situation predicates of any kind, your work should go in some microtheory that is a specialization of SituationPredicateRepresentationMt. These predicates allow Cyc to represent situations without positing the existence of situation particulars: instead of asserting (thereExists ?X (and (isa ?X Running) (performedBy ?X BritneySpears))), we make a statement having the same form as `Britney runs', e.g., (runs BritneySpears) or (does Running BritneySpears) -- notice the absence of existential quantifiers ranging over events in the latter representation. SituationPredicateRepresentationMt is the topmost microtheory for situation-predicate representation: _all_and_only_ domain-specific representation using SituationPredicates and the like should be placed in microtheories _below_ this one. Note further that conversion rules between situation-predicate and Davidsonian assertions (like the thereExists example above) should _not_ be asserted in this microtheory, but rather in some restricted context that is a specialization of #$Davidsonian-NonDavidsonian-ConversionMt (q.v.).

items.comment: An instance of Format (q.v.) that can be specified to hold of a given predicate with respect to a given argument-place (see argFormat). (argFormat PRED N SetTheFormat) means that, for any particular way of fixing the other arguments to PRED besides the Nth, there might be any number (including zero) of things such that, if taken as the Nth argument, PRED holds of those arguments. For example, the format of biologicalMother's first argument-place is SetTheFormat, since a female animal might have any number of offspring. Unlike the other reified instances of Format, SetTheFormat actually places no restriction at all on what PRED might or might not hold of with respect to the relevant argument-place. But one should not infer from this that entry-format assertions using SetTheFormat are pointless; for they forestall duplication of effort by serving notice that the entry-format of a given argument-place has previously been considered and SetTheFormat was deemed the appropriate format. SetTheFormat is the most commonly-encountered format in the Cyc Knowledge Base. Contrast with SingleEntry.

That is, if the sequences <... ARGN ...> and <... ARGN-PRIME ...> differ at most in their Nth items and both (PRED ... ARGN ...) and (PRED ... The second argument is a variable which uniquely identifies the existentially quantified variable by which the denoted skolem will be represented in the canonical version of the formula. The third is a sequence variable if there is a sequence variable argument of the denoted skolem function (which there will be iff there is a sequence variable in the scope of the bounded existential), and NIL otherwise. The function SituatedLinkFlowCapacityFn, applied to a link and the NetworkFlowSystem_Bounded of which it is a part, as in (SituatedLinkFlowCapacityFn LINK SYSTEM), denotes the net (usally calculated) 'flow capacity' for LINK taking into account the effects of its connections to the rest of SYSTEM. Here the 'flow capacity' is a number that is the measure of the maximum capacity of LINK, as restricted by any connections to other links, for the flow of something along the link, such as vehicles-per-hour, gallons-per-minute, or some other flow or quantity that conforms to the NetworkFlowSystem_Bounded rules. (To find out what kind of flow is assumed by a particular NetworkFlowSystem_Bounded, see the predicate flowTypeOfSystem.) Because it is a 'situated' or 'context-dependent' measure on LINK, it must take into account any flow bottlenecks upstream or downstream from it (for the local total capacity of the link in isolation, see LocalLinkFlowCapacityFn). Technical notes: The value of SituatedLinkFlowCapacityFn is often calculated from the LocalLinkFlowCapacityFn values of all the links in the PathSystem using an algorithm like the Ford-Fulkerson algorithm. Every link in a NetworkFlowSystem_Bounded has a direction. If the value of SituatedLinkFlowCapacityFn is negative, it refers to minimum flow in the backward direction. This is unusual.

items.comment: '(ResemblingTypeFn COLLECTION)' denotes the collection of things that resemble instances of COLLECTION. Since everything resembles itself, the collection returned will be a generalization of the collection used in argument 1. The returned collection represents the quality of 'being like', or 'resembling' a typical instance of COLLECTION (in some unspecified way). For example (isa MyCalculator (ResemblingTypeFn Computer)) says that my calculator is 'computer-like' is some respect. In English, one usually says things like 'Y is X-like' in order to convey that Y is not an X, or that one is uncertain whether Y is an X. However, this is a matter of implicature and not strict inference, so in Cyc all instances of X are such that they are, indeed, X-like.
